ðŸ§© Detect Cycle in Directed Graph (DAG Check)
ðŸ”¹ Intuition

A Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) should have no cycles.
If there is a cycle, we canâ€™t perform a valid topological sort because some nodes depend on each other in a loop.
We can detect cycles in two ways:

Using Kahnâ€™s Algorithm (BFS)
Using DFS with recursion stack

ðŸ”¸ 1. Using Kahnâ€™s Algorithm (BFS)

Kahnâ€™s Algorithm (used for topological sort) can also detect a cycle:
It repeatedly removes nodes with in-degree = 0.
If all nodes are processed â†’ No Cycle
If some nodes remain unprocessed (their in-degree never becomes 0) â†’ Cycle Exists

ðŸ”‘ Key Points

Works using in-degree and BFS traversal.
If number of processed nodes < total nodes â†’ Cycle Detected.
If all nodes processed â†’ No Cycle (graph is a DAG).

â±ï¸ Complexity
Time: O(V + E)
Space: O(V + E)

bool isCyclic(int V, vector<int> adj[]) {
    vector<int> inDegree(V, 0);

    // Step 1: Calculate in-degrees
    for (int i = 0; i < V; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < adj[i].size(); j++) {
            int neighbor = adj[i][j];
            inDegree[neighbor]++;
        }
    }

    // Step 2: Push nodes with 0 in-degree
    queue<int> q;
    for (int i = 0; i < V; i++) {
        if (inDegree[i] == 0) q.push(i);
    }

    // Step 3: Process queue (similar to topological sort)
    int count = 0;
    while (!q.empty()) {
        int node = q.front();
        q.pop();
        count++;

        for (int j = 0; j < adj[node].size(); j++) {
            int neighbor = adj[node][j];
            inDegree[neighbor]--;
            if (inDegree[neighbor] == 0)
                q.push(neighbor);
        }
    }

    // Step 4: If not all nodes processed â†’ cycle exists
    return (count != V);
}


Using DFS + Recursion Stack

Use two arrays:
visited[] â†’ marks visited nodes
pathVisited[] â†’ tracks nodes in the current DFS path
If during DFS we reach a node that is already in the current path, it means thereâ€™s a cycle.

Key Points

Uses DFS recursion and a pathVisited array.
If a node is revisited within the same recursion path, a cycle exists.
Works efficiently for directed graphs.

bool dfsCycle(int node, vector<int> adj[], vector<int> &visited, vector<int> &pathVisited) {
    visited[node] = 1;
    pathVisited[node] = 1;

    for (int i = 0; i < adj[node].size(); i++) {
        int neighbor = adj[node][i];

        // If neighbor not visited, do DFS
        if (!visited[neighbor]) {
            if (dfsCycle(neighbor, adj, visited, pathVisited))
                return true;
        }
        // If neighbor already in current path â†’ cycle
        else if (pathVisited[neighbor]) {
            return true;
        }
    }

    pathVisited[node] = 0; // backtrack
    return false;
}

bool isCyclic(int V, vector<int> adj[]) {
    vector<int> visited(V, 0);
    vector<int> pathVisited(V, 0);

    for (int i = 0; i < V; i++) {
        if (!visited[i]) {
            if (dfsCycle(i, adj, visited, pathVisited))
                return true;
        }
    }
    return false;
}
